aboutMe.intro: Hello, my name is Dave Gould and I love coding, both professionally and on my spare time. I have been an active developer for the past 5 years and it has become a part of who I am. I have created this digital resume, not only for you to get to know me, but also to showcase some development skills.

workExperience.intro: My experience in the workforce has been such an amazing journey. I am so lucky to have had the opportunities I've been given, and to have met such amazing people along the way. Below are the titles I have carried, in reverse chronological order. I have put on many hats since my first job at 14 years old. Although they might not be relevant, they are a part of who I am. Relevancy toggle is switched off to negate any irrelevant information and preserve my professional image as a software developer.

professionalProjects.name: Pershing Portal Framework
professionalProjects.introduction: Our internal Angular Framework, an ecosystem of core angular/node libraries, used by every front-end system in our company.
professionalProjects.description: My responsibility for this project was to contribute common components/functionality to this centralized layer for other features to utilize. When we got feature requests, I would analyze the best approach, create design doc/usage doc, clear it with my peers/managers, contribute, and support any usage questions/issues. Before joining, the existing framework developers were very picky about letting other (non-framework) developers contribute, I encouraged a more open source environment allowing other teams to contribute and send us PRs to achieve a more scalable model. It has worked out well so far!

professionalProjects.name: Sitebuilder
professionalProjects.introduction: An Application Similar to WIX or Squarespace where a user can create a branded instance of our interal platforms, Netx360 and NetxInvestor. Its also a developer admin tool!
professionalProjects.description: This was the project that stretched my technical and interpersonal leadership skills the most! My Director pulled me into this project that was in danger of failing and gave me less than 3 months to turn it around in time for our demo with the CEO. I worked day and night to understand the existing design. First, I identified the major refactories that would be needed to take us out of the technical deficit we were in (there was 2 junior developers working on this for over a year). Next, I restructured our sprint to prioritize the key items we would need to implement to achieve our goal. Finally, I shared the vision and provided guidance to the younger developers to grow their understanding so we could work in synergy. This project made its deadline for the demo and received very positive responses. They have kept me on, and we are now working on getting it to production!

professionalProjects.name: VR: User Navigational Patterns
professionalProjects.introduction: A VR Experience to visualize the navigational patterns of our users within our sites, which was demoed at an official conference with thousands of attendees. Visuialized using stars and planets. (Implemented using Oculus SDK and Unity)
professionalProjects.description: This was one of the most exciting projects for me because it merged my professional development skills with my interests in personal software development. Not many people in my field can say they created a VR app for their company that was demoed to thousands of people! For this project I was the sole contributor to the VR experience and I worked with one data scientist, who did the clustering of our user navigational patterns to get the data I needed. I created a rendering engine that rendered the nodes of our user data as planets and stars in a 3D space. Hovering over an item with the gaze pointer, you were able to view the edges (constellations) that connected the nodes, and details of the node itself through a beautiful virtual user interface. The user interface was rendered in 3D space with a closeup of the beautiful planet textures I used.

professionalProjects.name: Netx360 Mobile Hybrid
professionalProjects.introduction: A mobile channel for our web application that can be found on the Android and IOS app store.
professionalProjects.description: The goals for this project were to offer a performant mobile experience that was also scalable. We were in the midst of re-writing our angular web application, and it was not within the realm of feasibility to do another full re-write for our mobile channel. Thus we needed a way to build our web application to mobile. After diving deep into the project I came up with a solution where we could completely re-use our web-mobile experience, and build it using Ahead of time Compilation. Then I created a new angular service to allow our Angular features to invoke native device functions such as camera, gps. I wrote the node script which pulls all of our portal / feature modules, generates our menu and site configuration, builds the mobile app in AOT, and outputs an apk and ipa file which can be pushed to the appstore. I propsed my solution against existing prototypes and got buy in from our Director to have mobile team scale it out. As a result we now have a scalable solution that works for not only one of our products but our other platform NetxInvestor as well.

professionalProjects.name: Netx360 Wealth
professionalProjects.introduction: A complete rewrite of our legacy Netx360 stock trading application
professionalProjects.description: My role for this project was to get us in a position where we could retire our old platform (of 15 years). This involved designing new ways to tackle old problems, replacing components, retiring unneeded functionality. This was a great experience for me because re-writing legacy applications was something I was already familiar with, so I was able to excel and ask the right questions to promote innovation. Many times, people fall into the trap of replicating the same old functionality in a new application, because its safer. I always approached situations asking “why?” and that got me to some interesting places in my designs. Aside from standard application development I also got outside my comfort zone in the networking aspect. I implemented a new routing mechanism known as service discovery which is a replacement for DNS based routing, where in order to interact with another service you need to hardcode the domain urls.

professionalProjects.name: Account Opening API
professionalProjects.introduction: Lead the effort to expose our account opening service into rest API’s to be used by multiple internal platforms.
professionalProjects.description: For this effort my role was to support another team in creating accounts via REST API's. Prior to this, our account opening platform did not have any REST API's. Our service was only used by our account opening front end, and they were coupled together. For this effort, I introduced a new layer which was a spring microservice which interacted with our monolithic service via spring remoting, and exposed all of the functionality for creating accounts over HTTP.

professionalProjects.name: Digital Advice
professionalProjects.introduction: Lead the effort to integrate Digital Advice with our account opening process.
professionalProjects.description: After opening an account, I introduced a new async process (similar to kafka) which listens to the events sent to my Digital Advice team. When triggered, it will merge Digital Advice metadata with Account metadata, store and call multiple external systems. I also introduced a scheduler to handle any downstream system outage use cases.

professionalProjects.name: Client On Boarding
professionalProjects.introduction: Re-write of our existing Account Opening platform.
professionalProjects.description: I worked full stack on this project for about 2 years as my first project at Pershing. Initially, we were rewriting this application from server generated jsp to a legacy javascript framework called DOJO. Unsatisfied with my workday experience learning DOJO in the office, I took my laptop home with me every weekend and began porting to Angular 2, just to learn the newer framework for myself. After some time, I shared my work with my manager who-- after hearing from our leaders that we would be moving to Agular in a couple years-- encouraged me to keep going. I got recognized for my hard work outside of work and offered a job on another, larger-scale team.
